<h2>
    <strong>Rainbow Trout Behavior and Habitat Insights</strong>
</h2>
<p>
    Understanding rainbow trout behavior is key to consistently landing them. These fish are opportunistic feeders, responding to food availability, water temperature, and light conditions.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Habitat &amp; behavior essentials:</strong>
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Preferred Waters:</strong> Cool, oxygenated, clear waters—rivers with gravel bottoms and well-structured banks.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Feeding Patterns:</strong> Insects, minnows, and worms are top prey. They feed most actively in early morning and late evening.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Cover:</strong> Look for trout near submerged logs, undercut banks, deep pools, and riffle runs.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    In spring, trout move closer to the surface to feed on hatching insects. In summer, they seek deeper, cooler water.
</p>
<h2>
    <strong>Tips for Catching Bigger Trout</strong>
</h2>
<p>
    Want to land a trophy-sized rainbow? Here’s what local pros suggest:
</p>
<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>Fish Early or Late:</strong> Big trout feed during low-light hours to avoid predators and fishing pressure.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Use Stealth Tactics:</strong> Approach quietly, use long casts, and avoid flashy gear.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Match the Hatch:</strong> Use lures or flies that mimic local insects.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Target Deeper Water:</strong> Especially in warmer months, large trout hang near drop-offs or submerged structures.
    </li>
</ol>
<p>
    Using fluorocarbon leaders and smaller hooks can increase your catch rate with finicky or pressured fish.
</p>
